04724nam a22006135i 9780773555280DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20182018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735552807 a10.1515/97807735552802doi  a(DE-B1597)655500  a(OCoLC)1048895920  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aR9186.2 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a810.90052231 aHeidenreich, Rosmarin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterary Impostors :bCanadian Autofiction of the Early Twentieth Century /cRosmarin Heidenreich. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource :b8 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tFelix Paul Greve / Frederick Philip Grove: Being and Becoming -- tIn Search of Frederick Philip Grove -- tArchie Belaney alias Wa-Sha-Quon-Asin, or Grey Owl -- tWill James: A Lone Cowboy from Quebec -- tThe “Professional Indian”: Chief Buffalo Child Long Lance -- tHybrid Identities: The Eaton Sisters -- tConclusion -- tFPG and the Thomas Mann Connection -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the first half of the twentieth century, a number of Canadian authors were revealed to have faked the identities that made them famous. What is extraordinary about these writers is that they actually "became," in everyday life, characters they had themselves invented. Many of their works were simultaneously fictional and autobiographical, reflecting the duality of their identities. In Literary Impostors, Rosmarin Heidenreich tells the intriguing stories, both the "true" and the fabricated versions, of six Canadian authors who obliterated their pasts and re-invented themselves: Grey Owl was in fact an Englishman named Archie Belaney; Will James, the cowboy writer from the American West, was the Quebec-born francophone Ernest Dufault; the prairie novelist Frederick Philip Grove turned out to be the German writer and translator Felix Paul Greve. Chief Buffalo Child Long Lance, Onoto Watanna, and Sui Sin Far were the chosen identities of three mixed-race writers whose given names were, respectively, Sylvester Long, Winnifred Eaton, and Edith Eaton. Heidenreich argues that their imposture, in some cases not discovered until long after their deaths, was not fraudulent in the usual sense: these writers forged new identities to become who they felt they really were. In an age of proliferating cyber-identities and controversial claims to ancestry, Literary Impostors raises timely questions involving race, migrancy, and gender to illustrate the porousness of the line that is often drawn between an author's biography and the fiction he or she produces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Canadian. 0aAutobiographical fiction, Canadiany20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAutobiography. 0aCanadian literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCreative nonfiction, Canadian. 0aImpersonation in literature. 0aImpostors and imposture in literature. 0aLiterary forgeries and mystificationsxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311127363108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2018z978311127598740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773555280?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773555280423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773555280/original  a978-3-11-127363-1